sentences.text:
As the following analysis will demonstrate, Ms Wong was a person who was directly and indirectly knowingly concerned in, and party to, the contraventions by Dukemaster of ss 52, 53(e) and 51AC of the TPA referred to below by reason of her: 
(1) conducting on behalf of Dukemaster all of the dealings with each of Mrs Shin, Mr Tan, Mrs Lai, Mr Mei and Gomax (the tenants); 

(2) being aware of the oral and written statements from which the representations referred to below arose; 

(3) being aware of the facts and circumstances by reason of which the representations were misleading and deceptive and/or false; and

(4) knowing the facts and circumstances which constitute the conduct which was, in the circumstances, unconscionable.

Accordingly, the Act in section 37(2) makes the following provision for rent reviews based on current market rent:


 The current market rent is taken to be the rent obtainable at the time of the review in a free and open market between a willing landlord and willing tenant in an arm's length transaction having regard to these matters --- 


(a) the provisions of the lease;


(b) the rent that would reasonably be expected to be paid for the premises if they were unoccupied and offered for lease for the same, or a substantially similar, use to which the premises may be put under the lease;


(c) the landlord's outgoings to the extent to which the tenant is liable to contribute to those outgoings;


(d) rent concessions and other benefits offered to prospective tenants of unoccupied retail premises;


but the current market rent is not to take into account the value of goodwill created by the tenant's occupation or the value of the tenant's fixtures and fittings.

Those allegations fall to be considered under the following headings: 
(a) Renewal of First Shop 3 Lease / "negotiation" of Second Shop 3 Lease;

(b) Renewal of Second Shop 3 Lease / "negotiation" of Third Shop 3 Lease;

(c) March 2007.

(A) RENEWAL OF FIRST SHOP 3 LEASE / "NEGOTIATION" OF SECOND SHOP 3 LEASE
 The ACCC's first complaint was that Dukemaster's conduct in relation to the renewal of the First Shop 3 Lease / the "negotiation" of the Second Shop 3 Lease (see Annexure A) was unconscionable within the meaning of s 51AC(1)(a) of the TPA by reason of one or more of the following facts: 
(1) Dukemaster was, or should have been, aware of the lack of bargaining power of Mrs Shin because:


(a) at the time of the renewal, Mrs Shin had only been operating the Korean Lunch Box for nine months;


(b) Mrs Shin was unable to understand the process or the documents associated with the Second Shop 3 Lease given her very limited ability to speak and read English;


(c) Mrs Shin had no knowledge of her legal rights as a tenant under the Retail Tenancies Reform Act and did not understand that Rental Determination was an option available to her;


(d) the Korean Lunch Box was a very small business with limited scope of growth in revenue; and


(e) Mrs Shin needed to renew the First Shop 3 Lease for the remaining term of three years to recoup the investment she had made in the Korean Lunch Box;


(2) Dukemaster acknowledged Mrs Shin's exercise of her option to renew the First Shop 3 Lease and then offered Mrs Shin a new lease when it knew (or reasonably should have known) that Mrs Shin did not understand that she was entering into a new lease and by entering into that new lease (Second Shop 3 Lease), she would lose her right to Rental Determination in respect of the $48,000 Rent and that the $48,000 Rent would become subject to annual CPI adjustments;


(3) Dukemaster denied Mrs Shin adequate time to consider the $48,000 Rent including whether she should proceed to Rental Determination by not advising Mrs Shin of the $48,000 Rent until 27 November 2003, being less than three months before the First Shop 3 Lease would expire and requesting a response within 11 days, when:


(a) Mrs Shin wrote to Dukemaster about exercising the option to renew the First Shop 3 Lease on 16 September 2003;


(b) Dukemaster knew (or reasonably should have known) that Mrs Shin would need assistance in the relevant negotiations and completing the necessary documents; and


(c) Dukemaster knew (or reasonably should have known) that a rental increase of approximately 15% would be likely to decrease the profitability of the Korean Lunch Box.

(4) Dukemaster made the First and Second Shin Representations to Mrs Shin when the time made available to Mrs Shin to make her own enquiries about market value for the rent was limited particularly when Dukemaster:


(a) knew (or reasonably should have known) that the rental it was seeking was not the current market rent;


(b) had not obtained appropriate valuation advice or evidence in relation to the market rental for Shop 3 for the period from 1 February 2004 to 31 January 2005;


(c) had denied Mrs Shin adequate time to consider the $48,000 Rent;


(d) knew (or reasonably should have known) that Mrs Shin's ability to make her own enquiries about the market value for the rental was limited; and


(e) knew (or reasonably should have known) that the First and Second Shin representations were likely to influence Mrs Shin not to proceed to Rental Determination.

(5) Dukemaster required payment of the $48,000 Rent which was significantly higher than:


(a) the then current market rental for Shop 3 which if it had been applied would have required an increase of approximately 3%, not 15%;


(b) the rental being paid by Mrs Shin immediately prior to the commencement of the Second Shop 3 Lease.

(B) RENEWAL OF SECOND SHOP 3 LEASE / "NEGOTIATION" OF THIRD SHOP 3 LEASE
 With respect to the Third Shop 3 Lease, the ACCC contends that the circumstances said to give rise to a finding of unconscionability mirrored those set out in [126] in relation to the renewal of the First Shop 3 Lease / the negotiation of the Second Shop 3 Lease subject to the following modifications and exceptions: 
(1) in relation to circumstance (1) in [126], the ACCC relied upon contentions 1(b) --- 1(d), (though the Rental Leases Act was now in force) and further the ACCC contended that Dukemaster was, or should have been, aware of the lack of bargaining power of Mrs Shin because Mrs Shin needed a reasonable rent to enable her to continue to run the Korean Lunch Box Business and Mrs Shin needed a longer lease for Shop 3 to maximise the value of the Korean Lunch Box business;


(2) circumstance (2) in [126] was not relevant;


(3) in relation to circumstance (3) in [126], the ACCC relied upon the contentions except that the rent, of course, was not $48,000 but $90,000 and the ACCC contended that Dukemaster did not advise Mrs Shin until 3 January 2007, less than one month before the Second Shop 3 Lease would expire when:


(a) Mrs Shin wrote to Dukemaster about the lease over two months before 3 January 2007 (see [35]);


(b) Dukemaster knew the relevant rental range more than 4 months before 3 January 2007;


(c) Dukemaster knew (or reasonably should have known) that Mrs Shin would need assistance in the relevant negotiations and completing the necessary documents;


(d) Dukemaster knew (or reasonably should have known) that a rental increase of approximately 78% would be likely to significantly decrease the profitability and saleability of the Korean Lunch Box business;


(e) Dukemaster knew (or reasonably should have known) that as a result of it not giving Mrs Shin the written notice as required by s 28(1) of the Retail Leases Act , the time for Mrs Shin to exercise her option to renew the Second Shop 3 Lease was to continue until at least 6 months after the requisite notice was eventually given, which information it did not disclose to Mrs Shin;


(4) in addition to circumstance (3), the ACCC contended that Dukemaster required a response to the 3 January 2007 letter within 7 days over the New Year holiday period during which time: 


(a) Mrs Shin was unable to obtain legal advice in relation to the renewal of the Second Shop 3 Lease; and


(b) Dukemaster knew (or reasonable should have known) that Mrs Shin would have difficulty contacting her own lawyer or any lawyer;


(c) when Dukemaster failed to comply with its relevant obligations under s 28(1) of the Retail Leases Act .

(5) in relation to circumstance (4), the ACCC contended that Dukemaster made the Third to Seventh Shin representations (see [86]-[122]) to Mrs Shin when the time made available to Mrs Shin to make her own enquiries about the market value of the rental was limited particularly when Dukemaster:


(a) knew (or reasonably should have known) that the rental it was seeking was not the current market rental;


(b) had not obtained appropriate valuation advice or evidence in relation to the market rental for Shop 3 for the period from 1 February 2007 to 31 January 2008;


(c) knew that many tenants in the food court were paying significantly less than the $90,000 Rent at that time for premises comparable or similar in size to Shop 3;


(d) had denied Mrs Shin adequate time to consider the $90,000 Rent;


(e) knew (or reasonably should have known) that Mrs Shin's ability to make her own enquiries about the market value for the rental was limited; and


(f) knew (or reasonably should have known) that the Third to Seventh Shin representations were likely to influence Mrs Shin not to proceed to Rental Determination.

(6) in relation to circumstance (5), the ACCC contended that Dukemaster required payment of the $90,000 Rent which was significantly higher than:


(a) the then current market rental for Shop 3 which if it had been applied would have required an increase of approximately 0.1%, not 78%;


(b) the rental being paid by Mrs Shin immediately prior to the commencement of the Third Shop 3 Lease;


(c) the rental agreed to by Dukemaster at that time for Shop 6, Shop 11 and Shop 12 in the food court which were comparable / similar in size to Shop 3;


(7) by reason of the circumstances alleged by the ACCC above, the ACCC also contended that Dukemaster did not inform Ms Zu during the 3 January 2007 conversation that Rental Determination was an option if Mrs Shin still thought the $90,000 Rent was too high;


(8) the ACCC also contended that by Dukemaster offering Mrs Shin a new lease when it knew (or reasonably should have known) that Mrs Shin did not understand that by entering into the Third Shop 3 Lease (a new lease) she would lose her right to Rental Determination in respect of the $90,000 Rent;


(9) in relation to circumstance (6), the ACCC contended Dukemaster did not obtain appropriate valuation advice or evidence in relation to the market rent for Shop 3 for the period from 1 February 2007 to 31 January 3008 and particularly before making the Third to Seventh Shin representations.

(10) in addition, the ACCC contended that:


(a) Dukemaster refused to negotiate or to agree to reduce at all the rent payable under the Third Shop 3 Lease in the circumstances set out above;


(b) Dukemaster expressed its opinion as to the amount that would be the current market rental for Shop 3 as contemplated by cl 5.16A(a) of the Second Shop 3 Lease ($90,000 Rent) when Dukemaster did not genuinely believe that amount would be the current market rent and did not have a reasonable basis for its opinion.

Those allegations fall to be considered under the following headings: 
(a) Renewal of First Shop 4 Lease / "negotiation" of Second Shop 4 Lease;

(b) Renewal of Second Shop 4 Lease / "negotiation" of Third Shop 4 Lease.

In relation to Shops 1 and 2, those allegations fall to be considered under the following headings: 
(a) First Renewal in late 2003 / early 2004;

(b) Second Renewal.
